1. Summary of Situation

Over a two-week period, the credit scoring model has demonstrated a material increase in decline rates affecting a specific segment of applicants.

Decline rates increased by ~18% overall
Disproportionate impact observed in self-employed applicants with variable income profiles
Pattern identified through customer complaints rather than automated monitoring

There is no indication of system compromise or data breach.

The model is operating as designed.

That is the concern.

2. Why This Is Being Treated as an Incident

This does not meet the traditional definition of a security incident.

However, it meets the threshold of an AI governance incident.

The system is producing outcomes that may not be justifiable
The behaviour was not detected through existing controls
The impact is customer-facing and potentially systemic

If left unaddressed, this creates exposure beyond operational performance — specifically regulatory and reputational risk.

3. What We Currently Understand

Initial review suggests:

Recent model update introduced increased weighting on income stability indicators
These indicators correlate strongly with non-linear income patterns (e.g. self-employed customers)
No explicit rule exists targeting this group, but the outcome is functionally similar

There is currently no clear explanation that can be confidently provided to affected customers.

That is a more immediate issue than the model behaviour itself.

4. Impact Assessment
Customer Impact
Increased likelihood of unjustified credit refusal
Reduced transparency in decision-making
Elevated complaints risk
Regulatory Exposure

Relevant considerations include:

Fairness and transparency expectations under UK GDPR
Potential scrutiny under emerging AI governance expectations (EU AI Act alignment if applicable)
FCA expectations around customer outcomes and decision accountability

This is unlikely to trigger immediate reporting thresholds.
It may, however, trigger supervisory interest if identified externally.

Reputational Risk

This type of issue does not typically surface as a technical failure.

It surfaces as:

“Customers being treated unfairly by an automated system.”

That distinction matters.

5. Control Observations
Monitoring focused on model accuracy, not outcome distribution
No defined threshold for what constitutes unacceptable disparity in outcomes
Human oversight exists, but is not triggered at scale — only on individual review

In practical terms, the system failed quietly.

6. Immediate Actions Taken
Model update paused pending review
Retrospective analysis initiated on affected decisions
Customer support briefed to escalate relevant complaints
Internal review group convened (GRC, Data Science, Compliance)
7. Decisions Required from the Board
Model Continuation vs Suspension
Continue operating with controls, or suspend model pending remediation
Customer Remediation Approach
Whether to proactively review and potentially reverse affected decisions
Disclosure Position
Internal containment vs voluntary disclosure to regulator
Governance Adjustment
Agreement on what constitutes an “AI incident” going forward
8. Final Observation

No control failed in a way that would be captured by a traditional audit.

The system remained secure.
The model remained functional.

The failure was in how outcomes were produced and how long that went unnoticed.

This is not a gap in security.

It is a gap in governance.
